¹ W. Meyer commenting on these verses says “ differunt a simplici et puro genere dicendi, quod in sententiis est,'’ but that is only what one would naturally expect, as the sentences were chosen as such sor their peculiar sententious qualities. The Plautinian alliteration and word· manufacture and the references (e.g. to the Coan garments in ventum textilem) are certainly not unsuited to the age in which Publilius wrote, and the more than music-hall licence is just what tradition asserts to have been the most attractive and the chief demoralising feature of the mime.
